          "Getting next word in the sequence correct",
          "Correct (1) vs Incorrect (0)",
          "6000 language learners on SLAM dataset\n\nUnmentioned number on HLR",
          "3 Languages on SLAM: English, Spanish and French",
          "Exercise Sentences",
          "[Sequence of Preceding Words]",
          "DKT approaches learn from raw data, meaning that they cannot capture latent student behaviors.\n\nBKT is able to do that, but the model, on a results-based approach underperforms DKT.",
          "The model introduces a seq-to-seq form of knowledge modelling. While advantageous relative to DKT or BKT (theoretically), the sequence model has a drawback of being deterministic.\n\nThe authors also propose Variational Knowledge Tracing which adds a latent variable to each time step.",
          "In this experiment, each word in the sequence is understood as an exercise. Thus, the prediction task becomes predicting if the next word in the sentence will be correct or not.",
          "SDKT,\nVDKT,\nSelf-Ensemble of SDKT, Self-Ensemble of VDKT, GBoost Ensemble of SDKT, GBoost Ensemble of VDKT",
          "Holdout Method",
          "English \n\n{F1-Score: 0.564 - GBoost-VDKT, AUC: 0.863 - GBoost-VDKT}\n\nFrench\n\n{F1-Score: 0.575 - GBoost-VDKT, AUC: 0.859 - GBoost-VDKT}\n\nSpanish\n\n{F1-Score: 0.531 - GBoost-VDKT, AUC: 0.838 - GBoost-VDKT}",
          "Work proposes a new approach that uses sequences to see if students understand gramatical rules. \n\nAs a probabilistic model, VDKT encodes the understanding of these rules as a latent variable.",
          "No Cross-Validation, \n\nCould be generalized for other contexts. \n\nLatent variables only capture information extractable from the learning trajectories - something other data sources could probably capture.\n\n"
        ],
        [
          "Regression",
          "MOOC",
          "Correctly answering the word being practiced",
          "Recall Rate on student-word sessions",
          "Unmentioned number on HLR",
          "Vocabulary Learning Exercises",
          "Learner-word session traces",
          "[Sequence of previous words discovered on the platform]",
          "DKT approaches learn from raw data, meaning that they cannot capture latent student behaviors.\n\nBKT is able to do that, but the model, on a results-based approach underperforms DKT.",
          "The model introduces a seq-to-seq form of knowledge modelling. While advantageous relative to DKT or BKT (theoretically), the sequence model has a drawback of being deterministic.",
          "Word discovery is understood as a learning section. Thus, the authors save the “sequence” of the previous exercises done.\n\nModels use a Encoder-Decoder architecture.",
          "SDKT\nVDKT",
          "Holdout Method",
          "{MAE: 0.115 - VDKT, AUC: 0.552 - VDKT}",
